result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Troy J. Jensen was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The defendant shall not commit any criminal offenses during the period of this agreement.  Defendant shall notify the Taylor County District Attorney's Office and Clerk of Court's office of any change of address within 10 days of said change.  Prior to the expiration of the agreement defendant must undergo an AODA and all recommended follow through treatment.  Proof of assessment must be provided to the Taylor County District Attorney's office.  Defendant shall pay restitution to the victim in the amount of $10,015.35.  Restitution has been paid to the Clerk's office prior to the agreement being signed.  Defendant must successfully complete two years probation and all required conditions of probation.  Defendant shall comply with his conditions of bond.

judgments.dispoDesc: Pursuant to an agreement the court granted the state's motion for a deferred entry of judgment of conviction on this charge for a period of two years.  Upon successful completion of the agreement the state will move to dismiss count 1.

miscConds.notes: Restitution has been paid in full before sentencing.

Defendant shall have no contact with the victim.  Defendant shall write a letter of apology to the victim due within 60 days and preapproved by probation.  Defendant shall undergo counseling as deemed appropriate by probation.  Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol.  Per 973.09 defendant may leave the State of Wisconsin for employment purposes but if defendant does not comply with probation this provision may be revoked.    Defendant shall pay supervision fees as ordered by the Department of Corrections. If probation is ordered and ultimately revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used.
Defendant shall undergo and AODA and follow through with any recommendations.

timeConds.notes:
The defendant shall pay all sheriff and jail fees or costs allowed or imposed by law and the sheriff shall be entitled to a judgment against the defendant for any such unpaid fees or costs.  
Jail can be served in any county in the State of Wisconsin provided arrangements are made by counsel or the defendant, it is approved by the Taylor County Jail, and at no additional cost to Taylor County.  Court ordered that the jail sentence may be divided up for purposes of defendant's employment, but must be served within the first six months of probation.
